INTRODUCTIONS TO CONTAINERS AND DOCKER
    - WHAT ARE CONTAINERS
        - Dockers is a tool that lets you create, run, and manage containers by acting as the engine between your applications and the operating system. It packages an application with everything it needs—code, libraries, and dependencies—into an isolated container that runs the same on any machine, whether it’s your laptop or a production server. Docker uses a Docker Engine on top of the host operating system, making containers lightweight since they share the OS instead of needing a full one like virtual machines. For example, if you build a Node.js web app, Docker can package it with the exact Node version and dependencies so it runs perfectly on another developer’s computer or in the cloud; similarly, you could run a database like MySQL in one container and a backend API in another, and they won’t interfere with each other. This isolation and consistency are why Docker is so important in modern development and DevOps, as it allows you to build once and run anywhere reliably.

    - BENIFIT OF CONTAINERS 
        - One of the main benefits of containers is isolation. Each container has its own environment, which means applications are separated from one another and from the underlying system. This prevents conflicts and ensures that applications run smoothly without interfering with each other. For example, one application might require Python 2.7 while another needs Python 3.8. Normally, these different versions could cause issues if installed on the same system, but containers keep them completely separate, allowing both applications to run without any problems.
        
        - Another important benefit is consistency. Containers provide a consistent environment for applications, meaning the application will behave the same way no matter where it is deployed. This helps eliminate the common issue known as “it works on my machine.” This problem occurs when an application runs correctly on one developer’s computer but fails on another system due to differences in operating systems, dependencies, or configurations. For instance, an application developed on a Windows laptop may not work properly on a Mac. Containers solve this by packaging everything the application needs, including dependencies and configurations, so it can be moved from one machine to another and still run in exactly the same way.
        
        - Finally, containers are highly efficient compared to traditional virtual machines. Containers share the host operating system’s kernel, rather than running a full operating system for each application. This reduces overhead and allows more containers to run on the same hardware. As a result, containers start up much faster and use fewer resources. In contrast, virtual machines created using tools like VirtualBox require a full operating system to boot up, which takes more time and consumes more system resources. Containers avoid this by relying on the host system, making them lightweight and faster to use.
